<TEXT>
a judge on wednesday appointed guardians for a 
leukemiastricken boy and his two young halfsiblings whom the 
sick boys father wants tested as potential bonemarrow donors 
but the illinois supreme court later stayed any action by the 
guardians until it reconsiders its original order that they be 
appointed 
the high court gave no indication when it would reconsider that 
ruling supreme court spokesman john madigan said 
the father and the attorney for 12yearold jeanpierre bosze 
said they hope the boys 3yearold twin halfbrother and 
halfsister would be tested if the guardians overlook the 
objections of the twins mother 
mom is making the wrong decision in this case said the 
childrens father tamas bosze of suburban hoffman estates the 
children would decide differently if they were grown up 
if my brother asked me for a blood test i would say sure 
bosze said after the hearing 
jeanpierres doctor says a bonemarrow transplant is the boys 
only chance for survival and the twins offer the best chance of a 
match bosze who fathered the twins by a former girlfriend went 
to court to force the testing after the woman refused to allow it 
in an order july 18 circuit judge monica reynolds refused to 
order the tests saying it would be an invasion of the twins 
privacy 
the illinois supreme court last week sent the case back to 
reynolds with further hearing with an order that guardians be 
appointed for the three children 
beverly pekala an attorney for the twins and their mother 
nancy curran appealed the high courts order 
the trial record is replete with evidence that all children 
involved with this case have had their interests zealously 
protected pekala said 
but attorney edward jordan who represents jeanpierre said the 
more objective view provided by guardians can help the court as it 
tries to balance the benefits to the boy versus the risk pain or 
inconvenience to the twins 
jordan said in his appeal to the high court that he wants time 
to gather more evidence he said this might include further medical 
information and testimony by people who have been donors in other 
cases 
and if any parents whose children were donors want to come 
forward wed be happy to talk to them jordan said 
the boys father said that jeanpierres leukemia must be in 
remission before he can receive a transplant 
bosze said his son recently underwent five days of chemotherapy 
and that doctors are close to bringing the disease under control to 
allow the operation 
he said that many nonrelatives have volunteered as donors but 
none has proven to be compatible 
the guardians named by reynolds are both chicago attorneys 
sheldon engel for jeanpierre and charles fleck for the twins 
</TEXT>
