<TEXT>
the american heart association is urging doctors 
across the country to consider testing for lyme disease in patients 
with unexplained strokes 
the suggestion comes after neurologists at walter reed army 
medical center in washington dc reviewed 12 cases of stroke 
caused by the disease contracted in europe 
the serious and possibly permanent brain damage that may result 
from strokes make it imperative that infection with lyme 
disease be suspected in any atypical stroke neurologists 
eugene may and bahman jabbari wrote in the august issue of stroke 
a heart association journal 
jabbari is director of the epilepsy and neurophysiology section 
at walter reed 
i suspect strokes caused by lyme disease have occurred in the 
united states but none has been reported so far said may 
senior neurology resident at walter reed hopefully 
neurologists in the united states will start looking more closely 
for lyme disease infections in stroke patients 
the doctors were alerted to the lymestroke connection when a 
20yearold us army soldier was transferred to walter reed in 
january 1989 where it was determined he had suffered a stroke 
triggered by an infecting agent that causes lyme disease 
the spirochete borrelia burgdorferi is transmitted to humans 
mainly by certain species of ticks each about the size of a 
pinhead 
may and jabbari found 11 similar cases in scientific literature 
and determined that all 12 had experienced meningitis and all had 
been infected in europe 
but they noted that only a few of the european strains of the 
lyme spirochete are closely related to the strains that cause lyme 
disease in the united states 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

