<DOCNO> AP900815-0005 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
a state regulators group is warning consumers 
about con artists who may try to exploit the crisis in the persian 
gulf by peddling bogus oil gas and precious metals investments 
the north american securities administrators association has 
issued an investor bulletin to warn small investors about the 
latest scams tied to recent developments in the mideast 
the group is an association of state government regulators that 
periodically alerts the public to the latest twists in 
consumerrelated securities fraud 
people shouldnt expect to make money overnight susan e 
bryant president of nasaa said in a telephone interview tuesday 
if a legitimate oil company is going to profit from the mideast 
oil crisis its going to take a while 
she said the organization had no direct reports of persian gulf 
oilrelated scams but there are rumors that theyre on the 
streets 
we usually dont get the complete story until someone figured 
out they lost money which could be several years down the road 
she said 
a con mans best friend is a headline or television news flash 
out of the mideast that threatens a disruption of oil supplies to 
the united states said bryant who is also administrator of the 
oklahoma securities department 
con artists previously have seized on the scam potential of 
mideast turmoil including the 197374 arab oil embargo the 1979 
iranian revolution and the tanker war during the iraniraq war in 
the 1980s bryant said 
investors should realize there are hundreds of high pressure 
telephone sales operations in the united states that will be 
burning up the phone lines with these kind of pitches for 
nonexistent or blatantly abusive investments she said 
investors should not to give money to strangers who contact them 
by phone nasaa said it also advised checking out whether an 
investment is registered with state authorities and if the promoter 
is licensed 
the nasaa bulletin warned that crooks through high pressure 
telephone sales from temporary boiler room operations 
encourage investors to buy into oil partnerships for 5000 
10000 or more 
to sweeten the deal they say the gulf conflict will drive up oil 
or commodity prices and the investor will be getting in early 
enough to ride the price rise 
but nasaa advised the wells in question often dont exist 
belong to someone else or are dry even a legitimate oil field can 
take as long as two years to reach full production the bulletin 
stated 
war and the rumor of war also can drive up the price of precious 
metals such as gold silver and platinum historically used as 
investment hedges during times of uncertainty and attract scam 
artists hawking bullion and coins nasaa said 
investors should be particularly careful about promotions for 
bankfinanced or collateral loan programs involving gold or silver 
the salesperson usually has made extravagant or misleading 
claims about the profit potential and very often high commissions 
interest charges storage fees and other expenses make it 
extremely unlikely that an investor will see a penny of profit 
the bulletin said 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

