<TEXT>
east germanys top political party relieved 
its general secretary of his duties today after a news magazine 
said he had worked for the former communist secret police for 15 
years 
martin kirchner chief of the christian democratic union of 
prime minister lothar de maiziere was told to step aside pending 
an investigation of the accusations said party deputy chairman 
horst korbella 
kirchner was pushed aside shortly after the west german magazine 
stern reported in its latest edition that he worked for the 
notorious secret police as a paid informant for 15 years 
stern which cited as sources three former secret police 
members said kirchner was working for the intelligence network 
when he met last year with west german chancellor helmut kohl and 
other west german officials 
kirchner was on vacation and could not be reached for comment 
he has denied previous reports in the press that he had ties to the 
secret police known as the stasi 
the stern report is the latest of several accusations that 
prominent people in east germanys new democratic system were 
informers for the oncefeared domestic intelligence network 
in recent months there also have been widespread reports that 
the stasi harbored notorious leftist terrorists and may have 
plotted and carried out the assassinations of dissidents and 
refugees 
considered one of the most skilled intelligence services in the 
world the omnipresent stasi created an atmosphere of fear and 
intimidation that helped keep in power the government of former 
hardline communist leader erich honecker honecker was ousted in 
the fall by a popular prodemocracy uprising 
the stern report said kirchner reported to the stasi details of 
a meeting with kohl and other west german officials during the 
waning days of the former government 
kohls west german christian democrats helped turn the east 
german christian democratic union from a communistlinked puppet 
party into a sister party that will soon merge with its west german 
counterpart 
the stern report said kirchner supplied information from the 
meeting with kohl to the stasi so it could prepare for the days 
following honeckers fall 
the christian democrats won the most votes in east germanys 
first free elections on march 18 by promising to seek quick unity 
with west germany 
de maiziere has denied accusations that he also supplied 
information to the secret police 
stern said kirchner was paid monthly by the stasi and worked as 
an informant for the agency until a few days before the opening of 
the berlin wall on nov 9 
stern said two of the three former stasi members it quoted were 
kirchners bosses during his relationship with the secret police 
between 1978 and 1989 
the stasi had more than 80000 members but was believed to have 
had even more people working with it on a regular basis this group 
included educators scientists and numerous other people 
east germans are torn between seeking retribution and 
prosecuting former stasi agents and informants or granting a 
general amnesty 
</TEXT>
