<TEXT>
two out of three americans say they are 
following the action in the persian gulf very closely and 85 
percent of those polled say it is the most important news of the 
month a media organization reported today 
the times mirror center for the people amp the press said the 
level of interest was significantly higher than for news of 
previous actions involving us armed forces 
for example 60 percent said they paid very close attention to 
the december invasion of panama and 58 percent to the us air 
strikes against libya in 1986 compared with the 66 percent for the 
gulf developments 
times mirror said it was unprecedented to have 85 percent 
responding that the gulf action was the most important story the 
previous high was 56 percent for the invasion of panama 
the center is an arm of times mirror which publishes a number 
of newspapers and has other news media interests the center makes 
monthly surveys of public interest in the news 
it said the public was reasonably well informed about the gulf 
crisis with 66 percent knowing that the soviet union is supporting 
us efforts to get iraq to withdraw from kuwait almost as many 
64 percent knew that other countries were sending forces to saudi 
arabia to defend against an iraqi invasion 
the organization surveyed 1213 adults by telephone from aug 
912 the error attributable to sampling and other random effects 
is plus or minus 3 percentage points the center said 
the center also said that 30 percent of the public an unusually 
large proportion said they had followed news about the condition 
of the economy closely during the previous four weeks in may only 
18 percent said they were paying close attention to news about 
increasing interest rates and higher inflation 
still however just as was the case in june only 18 percent 
claimed to be closely following stories about the efforts of the 
administration and congress to cut the budget deficit 
</TEXT>
