<TEXT>
a conservationist vessel deliberately rammed two 
japanese fishing boats in the north pacific disabling equipment 
used to recover driftnets a crew member reported 
the action was part of a campaign to document and halt the 
incidental deaths of millions of seabirds marine mammals and sea 
turtles from driftnetting said chris keyser in a marine satellite 
telephone call tuesday to the associated press 
the sea shepherd ii operated by the sea shepherd conservation 
society came upon the sixboat japanese squid fleet monday about 
1500 miles north of honolulu said keyser a freelance writer 
aboard the britishregistered 196foot north sea trawler 
it was necessary to disable their fishing gear in order to put 
them out of operation said paul watson the skipper of the sea 
shepherd ii and founder of the radical conservation group 
it was also necessary to create an international incident to 
focus international attention on the issue he said 
the japanese driftnetters are in violation of the north pacific 
treaty on the protection of migratory seabirds which was signed by 
the japanese government watson said 
but he contended that us and japanese authorities for the past 
decade have done nothing to enforce the treaty which protects 22 
species of sea birds 13 of which are threatened or endangered 
were fed up with people just talking about it its about 
time someone did something to get these pirates out of here said 
watson who charged that the north pacific area has become a 
biological wasteland because of the driftnetters 
any consequences are worth the action we took the sea 
shepherd society has always taken responsibility for its actions 
and we have never committed a criminal act nor caused any 
injuries he said 
