<DOCNO> AP900815-0019 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
californias ban on political party 
endorsements in elections of judges and local government officials 
is unconstitutional because if violates freedom of speech a 
federal appeals court has ruled 
the 83 ruling of the 9th us circuit court of appeals is the 
second blow in two years to state laws restricting party 
endorsements last year the us supreme court struck down a 
california law that prohibited parties from endorsing candidates in 
their own partisan primaries 
this decision constitutes a charter of freedom for political 
parties state democratic chairman edmund brown jr the former 
governor said in a statement after tuesdays ruling lobbyists 
and special interest groups have enjoyed a free hand while 
official political parties have been left out of local government 
deputy city attorney burk delventhal of san francisco whose 
office defended the state law said the ruling could be damaging to 
local government and judicial independence if it led to widespread 
party endorsements in nonpartisan elections 
it would deprive local governments of the opportunity to have 
people with independent points of view who do not necessarily have 
to toe the party line to gain access to the public delventhal 
said he said no decision has been made on an appeal to the supreme 
court 
the ban on endorsements in nonpartisan local government school 
board and judicial elections was added to the state constitution by 
the voters in 1986 after the state supreme court had ruled that the 
endorsements were not prohibited by law 
sponsors of the 1986 measure claimed roots in the reforms of the 
1910s that sought to break the grip of bigmoney interests by 
weakening political parties one of the reforms was to make all 
local government offices nonpartisan 
the measure was immediately challenged by a diverse group of san 
francisco political activists backed later by the state democratic 
party us district judge alfonso zirpoli ruled in their favor a 
threejudge appellate panel overturned his decision saying the law 
was needed to protect nonpartisan elections but the larger panel 
on tuesday reinstated zirpolis ruling 
chief judge alfred goodwin in the majority opinion said 
parties and their members have rights of free speech and 
association that cannot be completely suppressed without a 
compelling reason he said nonpartisan elections had been 
adequately protected by keeping the parties out of the nomination 
process and restricting the candidates partisan activities 
in a separate concurring opinion judge stephen reinhardt 
joined by judge alex kozinski said the integrity of the political 
process is threatened not by parties but by the corrupting 
influence of money in politics 
keeping parties weak does not prevent corruption and may even 
encourage it reinhardt wrote officeholders and candidates must 
go directly to the big monied interests and beg for the funds 
necessary to finance their campaigns 
he also said that as long as california elects its judges it 
must leave the voters free rightly or wrongly to consider the 
political philosophy of the candidates banning party 
endorsements merely leaves the field free to special interests 
reinhardt said 
dissenting judge arthur alarcon said a party endorsement in a 
judicial race might be tempting to a frightened incumbent who has 
been subjected to media criticism for an unpopular decision 
alarcon said 
judge pamela rymer in a separate dissent joined by alarcon and 
judge ferdinand fernandez said allowing party endorsements would 
effectively destroy the nonpartisan system 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

