two grape growers have been charged with 
passing off inexpensive wine grapes as premium varieties 
brothers nick and frank bavaro who own vineyards and a grape 
brokerage in escalon in the san joaquin valley are at the center 
of a statewide grape scandal 
an indictment charged them with conspiracy mail and wire fraud 
and false statements to the united states bureau of alcohol 
tobacco and firearms in connection to the sale of wine grapes to 
seven northern california wineries 
the indictments from a federal grand jury were issued late last 
week 
if convicted of all charges each faces a maximum of 130 years 
in prison and fines up to 65 million 
lawyers for both brothers declined comment 
according to the indictment inexpensive grapes such as 
valdepena and french columbard were sold as expensive zinfandel 
chardonnay and other varieties the bavaros made 400 to 1200 per 
ton for grapes that usually sell for 100 to 200 per ton 
the brothers allegedly lied about at least 6500 tons of wine 
grapes valued on the wholesale market at about 4 million 
among the wineries that purchased the grapes in question were 
the delicato vineyards in manteca the lost hills winery in acampo 
and the robert mondavi winery in oakville 
