tens of thousands of east german farmers 
protested today on the square where communism was toppled to demand 
protection from freemarket forces crushing their industry 
late in the day east german prime minister lothar de maiziere 
fired four ministers who dealt most closely with the nations 
crumbling economy 
dismissed were finance minister walter romberg agriculture 
minister peter pollack economics minister gerhard pohl and justice 
minister kurt wuensche 
pollack presides over the economic sector of the nation that has 
been hardest hit by east germanys shift to a free market 
the estimated 30000 farmers who converged on east berlins 
alexanderplatz were part of a nationwide series of strikes 
at the protest farmers waved banners demanding protection from 
western competition and black flags of mourning to protest what 
they said was the imminent death of their industry 
ending agriculture with a clearance sale read a large 
greenandwhite banner spread high above the crowd a reference to 
the slashed prices at which farmers must now sell their goods 
just a few hours before de maiziere announced his removal 
pollack was pelted with eggs and tomatoes when he tried to speak to 
the protesting farmers 
the protest was the biggest yet among east german farmers the 
most militant and hardesthit section of the countrys troubled 
economy 
the economic merger of the two german states on july 1 opened 
the floodgates to western competition and east german grocery 
stores have been filling their shelves with western products 
the large sovietstyle collective farms that once had a captive 
market now are forced to price their products at market levels and 
many are unable to meet their formerly subsidized payrolls 
experts say up to half of the collectives which employ more 
than 800000 people are essentially bankrupt and doomed to fail 
soon up to 70 percent of the market has been lost economists say 
rainer prizkow who works on a pig farm in the city of 
neuruppin said his operation has sold no pork in the last month 
we wont survive the winter he said 
arno mittendorf held up a redandgold banner awarded to his 
collective by the former communist regime two years ago because the 
farm had the highest production in its district of neubrandenburg 
mittendorf an agricultural economist said production is the 
same but little is sold 
we can only pay our workers through september he said 
experts say up to 4 million of east germanys 88 million 
workers could lose their jobs as the nation makes the transition to 
the free market 
almost 1 million workers are either jobless or working shorter 
hours at lower pay under a west germanfinanced program to keep 
workers targeted for layoff on the job 
romberg a member of the leftleaning social democrats who are 
uneasy coalition partners in de maizieres broadbased government 
often clashed with the christian democrats who dominate the cabinet 
pohl is a christian democrat and the other two are not aligned 
with a party 
romberg has been accused of overstating east germanys economic 
situation and once predicted that the country would experience a 
hot autumn a reference to unrest prompted by high unemployment 
expected in the fall 
