two former state prosecutors pleaded guilty 
today to cocaine charges in federal court 
richard guida who headed the attorney generals criminal 
division until 1986 pleaded guilty to one count of cocaine 
distribution the offense is a felony punishable by up to 20 years 
in jail and a 1 million fine 
michael trant who was an associate deputy attorney general 
pleaded guilty to one count of cocaine possession he could be 
sentenced to up to one year in jail and fined 5000 
the pleas were entered before us district judge edwin kosik 
guida and trant who served under former state attorney general 
leroy zimmerman waived indictments and pleaded guilty to the 
charges 
federal prosecutor gordon zubrod said in court that guida 
provided cocaine to friends on a number of occasions between august 
1985 and october 1987 during part of that period he worked as a 
state prosecutor 
zubrod said the government found no evidence to show that guida 
sold cocaine 
guidas plea is conditional on the outcome of a related appeal 
guida earlier pleaded guilty to the lesser charge of cocaine 
possession but that agreement was dissolved at the request of 
federal prosecutors who accused guida of withholding information 
he appealed 
if guida loses the appeal todays plea would stand if he wins 
the earlier plea would be reinstated 
both men are to be sentenced later 
