christian democrats who dominate the cabinet 
pohl is a christian democrat the other two fired ministers are 
not aligned with a party 
romberg has been accused of overstating east germanys economic 
woes and once predicted that the country would experience a hot 
autumn a reference to unrest that could be prompted by high 
unemployment expected in the fall 
farmers have been especially hardhit by east germanys shift to 
a free market after four decades of socialism 
on wednesday about 50000 farmers converged on the 
alexanderplatz the sprawling east berlin square where protests 
last year helped topple communist rule they were among hundreds of 
thousands of farmers who took part in a series of twohour strikes 
rallies and other protests across the country 
the farmers waved black flags to mourn their dying industry and 
listened to farm leaders demand an economic bailout from both 
german states which are expected to unify by years end 
the economic merger of the two german states july 1 opened the 
floodgates to western competition and east german grocery stores 
have been filling their shelves with western products 
the bloated sovietstyle collective farms that once had a 
captive market now are forced to price their products at market 
levels and many are unable to meet their formerly subsidized 
payrolls 
farmers are sitting on thousands of tons of unsold pork beef 
produce and grain 
experts say up to half of the collectives which employ more 
than 800000 people are essentially bankrupt and doomed to fail 
soon up to 70 percent of the market has been lost economists say 
rainer prizkow who works on a pig farm in the city of 
neuruppin said his operation has sold no pork in the last month 
we wont survive the winter he said 
