<TEXT>
a combination of rising business sales and 
falling stocks on shelves and back lots in june put inventories at 
their most favorable level in at least six years the government 
said wednesday 
its a rather impressive decline in inventories said 
michael k evans head of evans economics inc a washington 
forecasting firm one of the reasons we start a recession is that 
inventories get out of line and theres no evidence of that 
happening 
it means theres room for more growth if sales hold added 
michael p niemira an economist at mitsubishi bank in new york 
who said the inventory correction that began at the beginning of 
the year apparently continues 
in fact niemira said the decline in inventories combined with 
strong sales probably means a much better balanced economy in the 
second quarter than the government first estimated last month 
the commerce department said wednesday that sales jumped 10 
percent in june to a seasonally adjusted 5444 billion the same 
rate of increase as in may the advances were the strongest since 
february when sales rose 14 percent and regained a 10 percent 
decline in april 
inventories meanwhile dropped 04 percent to a seasonally 
adjusted 7973 billion down 31 billion from may when 
inventories posted a 05 percent advance it was the largest drop 
since a similar 04 percent decline in february 
the combination produced a 146 ratio of inventories to sales 
the lowest ratio since this series began in 1982 a commerce 
spokesman said the ratio means it would take 146 months to 
exhaust the backlog of goods at the june pace the ratio stood at 
149 in both april and may 
if inventories were to pile up excessively while sales slowed 
it could prompt businesses to cut back purchases resulting in a 
drop in production and job layoffs 
in its initial estimate of secondquarter growth the commerce 
department reported last month the 12 percent gain in the gross 
national product was due almost entirely to a big buildup in 
business inventories other major components of the economy 
declined 
the initial report on the gnp the nations total output of 
goods and services will be revised twice including the first 
reexamination on aug 24 when the june salesinventory report is 
taken into account 
wholesalers showed the biggest sales gain in june 17 percent 
while retailers posted a 11 percent advance and manufacturers a 
05 percent increase 
wholesalers had a 08 percent decline in inventories followed 
by a 05 percent drop by manufacturers retail inventories on the 
other hand edged up 01 percent 
