one of every four births in the united states 
in 1988 was to an unwed mother the government said wednesday the 
1 million births to unmarried women was an 8 percent increase over 
the previous year 
the report by the department of health and human services said 
that while the rates for children born out of wedlock were highest 
among black women the rates have been rising faster for white 
mothers 
the statistics also saw a rise in births to young teenagers for 
the second straight year after declining through much of the 1970s 
and 1980s there were 338 births per 1000 population to 
teenagers ages 15 to 17 
hhs said the largest annual increase for any age group was to 
women ages 40 to 44 up 9 percent from 1987 and 20 percent over 
1985 birth rates for women in their 30s have risen more than 40 
percent since 1975 
nearly two in three births to unwed mothers was among blacks and 
it was one in three for hispanics for whites the proportion was 
nearly one out of five the overall average was one in four 
the highest levels of births to unmarried mothers continued to 
be among women ages 18 to 24 hhs said 
since unmarried mothers are much less likely than married 
mothers to begin prenatal care early the proportion of women 
beginning such care in the first trimester showed no improvement 
through the 1980s and remains at 76 percent hhs said 
the percentage was particularly low among black and hispanic 
women 
