<TEXT>
closer federal supervision is needed to avoid 
a savingsandloan style crisis among governmentsponsored 
enterprises providing lowcost loans to home buyers farmers and 
students congressional auditors said wednesday 
the government has little ability to identify prevent or 
contain the effects of the kinds of problems that have led to 
taxpayer losses in the past the general accounting office said 
in a report 
the gao as required by last years sampl bailout bill examined 
the potential for a similar crisis among eight socalled 
governmentsponsored enterprises with collective obligations of 
more than 800 billion 
it said closer government oversight was needed of three of the 
biggest sallie mae which finances four of every 10 college loans 
and fannie mae and freddie mac which together finance about one 
fourth of the nations home mortgages 
the enterprises were created by congress but earn profits for 
private stockholders they are more formally known respectively 
as the student loan marketing association the federal national 
mortgage association and the federal home loan mortgage corp 
while there is no evidence that any of the enterprises are in 
danger of immediate failure the gao said they have many of the 
same unhealthy incentives that existed in the thrift industry 
they are not explicitly guaranteed by the government but most 
private investors assume congress and the administration would not 
stand idly by were one to near failure 
it seems clear that the federal ties cause investors to 
behave like insured depositors who believe their investments to be 
very safe the report said 
in fact congress in 1987 approved 4 billion in 
governmentguaranteed bonds to prop up the farm credit banks and 
the banks for cooperatives which finance agriculture 
because of the perception of government backing for the 
enterprises it is easy for them to raise money even when they are 
ailing the gao said 
the enterprises can continue to borrow money in private 
markets even when performing poorly the gao said 
in financially troubled times after capital is depleted 
owners and managers may have incentives to take unusual risks in a 
lastditch effort to recover it said 
the gao recommended that private investors in the enterprises be 
required to put up more of their own money or capital to insulate 
taxpayers from risk and provide an incentive against reckless 
behavior 
and the risktaking and capital levels of fannie mae freddie 
mac and sallie mae need closer government supervision it said no 
agency oversees sallie mae while the department of housing and 
urban development oversees fannie mae and freddie mac 
the auditors expressed skepticism that hud whose mission is to 
provide americans with affordable housing could properly ensure 
the safety of fannie mae and freddie mac 
the department has not provided the kind of safety and 
soundness supervisory controls normally imposed by banking 
regulators the gao said 
the government cannot depend on the department to reconcile 
its role as a safety and soundness regulator with its role as a 
promoter of housing it said 
other enterprises included in the report were the federal home 
loan banks which provide money for home mortgages the college 
construction loan insurance association which supports 
construction on college campuses and the federal agricultural 
mortgage corp which supports farming 
the gaos findings are similar to the conclusions in a treasury 
department study issued in may in that report the bush 
administration backed a controversial proposal to require 
governmentsponsored enterprises to meet the standards applied by 
independent creditrating agencies to the healthiest private 
corporations with triplea ratings 
the gao said it would present more specific recommendations when 
it issues a second report due next may wednesdays report was 
issued three months late 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

