<TEXT>
president bushs advisory panel on the 
treatment of cancer and aids proposed major changes wednesday in 
government testing of experimental drugs to speed them to patients 
for whom time is running out 
for patients who are not benefited by approved and readily 
available medicines still unproved therapies may represent their 
only hope the panel said in its final report 
for patients who resist all available therapies new 
treatments on the cutting edge of science may represent the best 
standard of care it said 
the presidents cancer panel chaired by industrialist armand 
hammer a physician by training concluded that patients are 
willing to accept the risks associated with new and untried 
therapies 
but it said they can become more widely available only if the 
food and drug administration the agency charged with approving and 
regulating medical therapies can be allowed and is willing to 
become more flexible in implementing such innovations for 
patients for whom time is running out 
activist groups representing aids and cancer patients also have 
called for expediting and expanding use of experimental treatments 
the panel made these recommendations and findings 
the secretary of health and human services should establish a 
permanent policy and oversight committee to monitor the fdas 
regulation and approval of drugs and biologic therapies for human 
use 
expedited approval of cancer and aids drugs could result if the 
fda relied more frequently on the opinion of qualified experts 
serving on agency advisory committees 
the fda should consider modifying its current criteria for 
approval of new drug applications the present standard proof of 
improved survival might well be changed to include complete or 
partial positive responses in patients whose cancers have resisted 
all current therapies 
the panel said drugs that produce tumor regression in more than 
20 percent or 30 percent of patients in approval trials should be 
approved for marketing 
congress should give prompt attention to fdas inadequate 
resources staff and facilities 
fda studies designed to determine if a drug under investigation 
is superior to that of a prescription drug may no longer be 
required for that drug to receive market approval 
the fdas advisory committee system for human prescription 
drugs should be fundamentally restructured with panels permitted to 
bypass intermediate staff and report directly to the fda 
commissioner the panels should have an independent staff and 
control their own agendas and priorities 
the panel also recommended that companies sponsoring 
experimental drugs have the option of paying the fda for outside 
review of the applications by qualified and unbiased experts in 
order to resolve the fdas problem of increasing responsibilities 
and decreasing staff 
medicare medicaid and private insurers should give identical 
coverage for experimental drugs and all related medical care for 
aids and cancer patients the committee said 
we endorse the development of communitybased clinical trials 
that permit widespread access to investigational drugs without 
sacrificing statistical analysis of drug effectiveness and thus 
that can lead to early regulatory approval the panel said 
hammer said he hopes the report will prove useful in improving 
the federal drug review process and in reducing delays in 
marketing new drugs thus benefiting cancer and aids patients 
throughout the country 
the study was initiated in june 1988 at the request of president 
bush then serving as vice president 
</TEXT>
