panama said wednesday it will 
continue to allow iraqi and kuwaiti ships through the panama canal 
citing the 1977 treaties with the united states guaranteeing 
neutral operation of the waterway 
foreign minister julio linares said panama is putting the panama 
canal treaties above all other international agreements including 
those under the un charter last week the un security council 
imposed a mandatory economic embargo against iraq for its aug 2 
invasion of kuwait 
according to the panama canal commission 27 kuwaiti ships 
passed through the canal last year only two ships flying the iraqi 
flag have made the passage in the last seven years the commission 
said 
in an interview linares said the united nations could have no 
legal objection to panamas decision to abide by the 1977 treaties 
the 1977 agreement declares the neutrality of the canal so 
that in times of peace as in times of war it will remain secure 
and open to the peaceful transit of the ships of all nations so 
that the canal and the isthmus of panama will not be the target of 
reprisals in any conflict between other nations of the world 
the panama canal commission issued a brief statement wednesday 
saying there has been no change in current policy in respect 
to the transit of ships through the panama canal 
president guillermo endara said that both the united states and 
panama agree that ships should be able to pass through the canal 
no matter what their nationality 
the united states and other western nations have amassed a large 
naval force in the middle east to stop shipping into and out of 
iraqi and kuwaiti ports 
the panama canal treaties call for control of the waterway to be 
turned over to panama at the turn of the century with that nation 
guaranteeing the neutral operation of the canal 
in 1979 panama took control from the united states of the canal 
zone which extends for five miles on either side of the waterway 
between the pacific ocean and caribbean sea 
