<TEXT>
an indicator of smaller business optimism has 
fallen to its lowest level since 1982 suggesting the economy isnt 
likely to regain strength before the end of the year 
the indicator an index based on analysis of more than 2000 
responses from members of the national federation of independent 
business was completed before the iraqi invasion of kuwait 
developments in the mideast will undoubtedly increase 
uncertainty said william dunkelberg who interprets the results 
dunkelberg an economist is dean of temple universitys school of 
business and management 
he said the deterioration in confidence reflects an economy that 
is going down at least for the count of 2 or 3 but that no 
particular aspect of the economic situation could be blamed more 
than another 
rather said dunkelberg each index component continued to 
reflect the slow deterioration apparent in the data for some 
time an erosion he describes as slow motion 
the index begun by dunkelberg in 1974 is based on detailed 
responses regarding expected business conditions climate for 
expansion sales volume credit conditions job openings capital 
outlays inventories hiring and more 
these responses are formulated into the index which ranks 1978 
conditions as 100 it fell to a seasonally adjusted alltime low of 
811 in the second quarter of 1980 and reached its high of 1087 in 
1984s first quarter 
the latest reading of 982 for the third quarter 1990 down from 
1008 in the second quarter was the lowest since 953 was recorded 
in the third quarter of 1982 shortly thereafter the index ascended 
into 100plus levels 
while the index is valued as a measurement of privatesector 
strength or weakness it is watched also because of its fairly 
accurate record in forecasting future economic conditions 
based on responses to the latest survey dunkelberg believes the 
inflation outlook may continue to improve that pressure from labor 
costs may ease and that the jobless rate likely will edge up as the 
year ends 
still he believes inflation fears will prevent the federal 
reserve from any major easing of credit conditions at best he 
suggests the fed will make ease noises rather than take strong 
action 
the companies on which dunkelbergs analyses are based all 
members of the national federation range from very small companies 
proprietorships and the like to companies with annual sales of 
more than 100 million 
none of these companies would qualify by size for lists of the 
1000 largest companies which generally are said to constitute 
big business broadly categorized therefore they are 
small 
the community they represent the federation says involves a 
vast and varied number of companies employing about onehalf the 
nations private nonfarm work forces and producing about 50 
percent of gross national product 
as such says dunkelberg they provide a grassroots view of 
attitudes and experiences that add up to an accurate picture of 
present conditions and an indication of what lies ahead 
economically 
while reminding people that the survey was conducted shortly 
before the latest oil problems he doesnt foresee dramatic changes 
ahead 
the expansion was not characterized by any extremes and it is 
consequently likely that the slowdown that follows will be equally 
boring he said 
