<TEXT>
deciphering airline fares never has been easy 
for passengers and the latest gyrations caused by the rising cost 
of oil are making the picture more frustrating than a rushhour 
runway backup 
thats why many travel agents have started urging clients to 
book flights several months ahead of time fearing that airlines 
inevitably will push fares higher to compensate for an enormous 
jump in jet fuel prices 
im writing tickets for february march and april said ben 
chanowitz an agent at travel magic a manhattan travel agency 
were recommending that people lock in now 
even for veteran air passengers the past week has been one of 
the more confused periods in the economics of air fares a 
convoluted science crammed with fineprint limitations 
first most airlines announced fare increases of more than 5 
percent to defray unexpected increases in jet fuel prices caused by 
the crisis in the oilrich persian gulf 
but on monday eastern airlines and trans world airlines two of 
the most financially weak carriers cut certain fares by up to 40 
percent to stimulate sales competitors matched them 
then on tuesday all major airlines delayed fuel surcharges by a 
week evidently out of partial fear that they could discourage 
wouldbe travelers from flying 
the net result is an atmosphere of uncertainty that is 
convincing a growing number of travelers to postpone plans or buy 
tickets now for thanksgiving christmas and beyond travel agents 
said 
we are encouraging people to buy whatever is available at the 
moment said juergen krenzien president of paul klein travel 
service in chicago our feeling is fares arent going down 
theyre going to go up 
others said it was a good idea to buy tickets now even if prices 
decline over the next few months because generally airlines will 
reissue the same tickets at the lower fare and refund the 
difference to the buyers 
but that generalization is loaded with some important 
exceptions especially in the case of discounted advancepurchase 
tickets that in many cases are nonrefundable 
the widely accepted rule is that airlines will only exchange the 
more expensive ticket for the cheaper one if the class of ticket is 
identical and the itinerary remains unchanged 
say youre holding a nonrefundable ticket for 200 and a 
lower fare is introduced at 150 all you do is contact a travel 
agent and you may switch to the lower fare said jackie pate a 
spokeswoman for delta air lines 
but there are conditions she said you cant change the 
flight or date if you were holding the 7day advance purchase 
nonrefundable and the new fare is a 14day nonrefundable then 
you may not be able to switch 
even with all the airfare uncertainty many travel agents say 
some good bargains are likely to endure especially going into the 
fall travel season that historically is one of the years slowest 
periods 
for example one of the most popular discounts a 14day 
advancepurchase nonrefundable ticket still offers a 40 percent 
discount off the peak price however its generally only good for 
tuesday wednesday and saturday travel 
moreover if youre a senior citizen you can get some of the 
best discounts because airlines and hotels have targeted people in 
their 60s as one of their most lucrative untapped markets some 
airlines offer packages to seniors that save hundreds of dollars on 
tickets with few limitations 
some travel experts are even predicting airlines will be forced 
to lower fares they speculate carriers might face a passenger 
boycott if they hike prices substantially to defray jet fuel costs 
which have jumped 25 percent and more since iraq seized kuwait aug 
2 and provoked world fear of an oil shortage 
the airlines have panicked over the fuel situation said 
eric munro chief executive officer of the san diego office of 
uniglobe worldwide travel but people are going to refuse to fly 
lets face it 
others said it was more likely that the airlines eventually will 
seek to minimize any fuelrelated increases and that many travelers 
probably wouldnt notice the rise in cost 
ten or 15 bucks just isnt going to make any difference for a 
bunch of people said herbert teison editor of the newsletter 
travel smart for business 
</TEXT>
