<TEXT>
an extensive study of celibacy among roman catholic priests 
finds that only half of them adhere to the discipline and that the 
subject itself is largely unexamined and confined to a realm of 
the secret 
psychotherapist a w richard sipe a resigned roman catholic 
priest who made the 25year study involving 1000 priests and 500 
of their intimates said the church shuns exploring realities of 
the celibacy requirement 
to church officials it cant be talked about in any way of 
actually discussing it he said it cant be questioned or 
logical arguments put forth about it 
all that is considered acceptable is to reiterate the party 
line 
sipe 57 a lecturer in the psychiatry department of the john 
hopkins university medical school in baltimore and also in private 
familytherapy practice there added in an interview 
an astounding thing not one seminary in the country has a 
course on celibacy not one even has a course on the history of 
celibacy so my church demands a state of celibacy without 
educating about it or supporting it 
sipe whose findings are to be detailed in a book a secret 
world sexuality and the search for celibacy to be published 
next month by brunnermazel said the church avoids the issues 
it relegates that activity to the area of the secret to a 
secret world he said you cannot have christian responsibility 
and put an important part of it in a secret world 
roman catholicisms rule of priestly celibacy is not a doctrine 
of faith but a clerical discipline it was not required until the 
12th century 
even afterward some priests bishops cardinals and even an 
occasional pope were married and concubinage flourished for 
centuries among clergy vowed to celibacy sipe said 
his findings came as surveys indicate a rising majority of us 
priests and laity favor optional celibacy allowing marriage 
for priests who chose it 
on the basis of his largescale data sipes estimates 50 percent 
of priests uphold celibacy to a great extent while the other 50 
percent violate it twenty percent have regular relationships with 
women he said 
many of these relationships are remarkably durable and 
personally compatible with the practice of ministry he added 
some behaviors of course are exploitative and pathologically 
determined 
in a preliminary summary of his findings last saturday to a 
convention of the american psychological association in boston 
sipes said another 6 to 8 experiment with noncelibacy in a 
datinglike behavior 
additionaly 10 to 13 percent of priests are active homosexuals 
he said while 6 percent involve themselves sexually with children 
or minors in most cases homosexually 
one percent practice crossdressing transvestism and 5 percent 
involve themselves in problematic sexual activity such as 
pornography and compulsive masturbation 
sipes said masturbation which the church condemns is a great 
conundrum for the student of celibacy because it is a common 
occurrence about 80 percent of priests do it occasionally 
of the half of priests upholding celibacy sipes said only 2 
percent have firmly achieved celibacy in a mature sense while 
another 6 to 8 percent despite missteps have solidly established 
the discipline 
additionally he said 40 percent of priests are practicing 
celibacy sufficiently well enough to be called celibate although 
unresolved personal and spiritual issues sometimes bring 
noncelibate behavior 
sipe who left the priesthood in 1970 to marry said his study 
identified four essential elements that make for a mature 
adjustment to celibacy namely 
productive work a welldefined prayer life a deep sense of 
community and a dedication to service 
the study conducted from 1960 through 1985 involved indepth 
interviews and reports from 1500 people a third of them priests 
in psychotherapy a third priests in other settings and a third 
lovers or others closely associated with priests 
he said that despite the obscurity in which celibacy has been 
shrouded and the lack of objective study of it celibacy has been 
a powerful factor in spiritual and cultural achievement in both the 
west and east 
however he said the present church approach is crippled by 
inadequate training of priests in human sexuality generally and by 
lack of education in celibacy itself 
considering the wraps kept on the subject preventing genuine 
proandcon analysis of it sipes said 
i say that bishops dont know any more about celibacy than 
priests and that you would find among bishops the whole spectrum of 
sexual adjustment and problems just as you do among priests 
it is logical to assume that bishops suffer the same sexual 
pressures as priests and if priests get involved sexually bishops 
must also there is no question about this the further i go in 
this study the more surprises there are about what goes on 
