<TEXT>
recent highprofile campaigns to locate 
bonemarrow donors have overshadowed a worrisome plight the 
nations two major bonemarrow registries are at odds 
wideranging campaigns to enlist potential donors have created a 
backlog of blood samples for testing and when the tests finally 
are done not all patients get access to the results partly 
because the two registries have acted in competition not in 
concert 
their failure to share information is more than a bureaucratic 
tangle it wastes time and time is the one thing these dying 
patients dont have 
patients are caught in the middle acknowledges liz quam 
spokeswoman for the national marrow donor program which has been 
criticized by its smaller rival the american association of bone 
marrow registries 
the country and the patients are not going to be helped to the 
fullest with these two groups fighting like dogs and cats said 
claude lenfant director of the national heart lung and blood 
institute 
a marrow transplant is the last hope for thousands of patients 
with leukemia aplastic anemia and other diseases but time is 
precious in the search for a donor 
you dont have an extra day or month said bonnie lundquist 
of fort lauderdale fla who searched for months for a transplant 
for her husband peter he died in february a week after 
potential donors were found 
the odds of finding a perfect match are at best 20000to1 
so the bigger the pool of donors the better the chance 
the national marrow donor program a quasigovernmental agency 
is the nations largest donor bank with more than 150000 names 
american has 35320 potential donors and also offers lowcost 
access to foreign registries 
about 10000 americans a year search for a marrow match public 
awareness about transplants has burgeoned in the past eight months 
largely because of people like leukemia patient allison atlas 
20 of bethesda md 
her determined supporters friends of allison ran a highly 
publicized search for a perfect marrow match that raised 3 million 
and enrolled 50000 potential donors atlass quest was 
unsuccessful she got an imperfectly matched transplant from her 
mother before time ran out 
national based in st paul minn hopes to one day have the 
nations sole registry it is supported in part by federal funds 
and draws on 70 major blood banks for its donor base 
americans registry based in mandeville la is a network of 
communitybased donor pools and gets no federal funds each local 
pool began to help a particular patient then expanded to aid other 
patients before joining in a network 
the rift between the two registries came to light in february in 
a congressional staff paper cowritten by health policy analyst 
hellen gelband who noted a lack of coordination from the patients 
perspective 
people didnt always find out that there were different 
registries they could go to gelband said in an interview 
have deaths occurred because patients werent aware of all their 
options 
youd have a hard time documenting it but it could have 
happened certainly she said 
we get kids whove been searching with national eight to nine 
months and found nothing and dont have eight weeks left when we 
get them said joanne raymond executive director of american 
when im talking to the mother of a 6yearold who died 
yesterday because we had a donor but they didnt get to us in time 
i cant see the big picture any longer she said 
critics say there are two basic obstacles patients dont know 
where to turn and the donor banks dont share their resources 
national started sharing donor lists with american on april 16 
but its data is too incomplete for a successful search raymond 
said and american thus far has refused offers to merge with the 
larger national 
the reason says the congressional paper major philosophical 
differences having to do with transplant center access costs 
search information and approval of transplant centers 
national requires patients to be admitted to costly hospital 
transplant centers before they can search its donor registry at 
american patients can search with permission from their doctors 
without entering a center 
national says transplant centers ensure that donors get the best 
possible care and dont waste their time giving marrow to a patient 
who isnt eligible for transplant or properly prepared for surgery 
quam said the centers also relieve unqualified patients of false 
hope 
american believes in trying even when the odds seem impossible 
and while national focuses on donor protection with an eye 
toward research raymond says shes more oriented toward patients 
the congressional paper said the price of searching for a match 
and harvesting bone marrow varies substantially by transplant 
center even though the center itself is minimally involved in 
those activities and is paying the registry for those services 
gelband found that patients who never find a successful match 
spend an average of 4000 and sometimes up to 15000 patients 
who go through transplants can spend 100000 to 200000 
depending on whether there are complications said quam 
american and national are considering proposals that would help 
them work together though neither side will discuss them yet 
congress also is looking at the rivalry for now the turmoil 
continues in court battles and press releases 
until recently the lifesavers foundation of america based in 
covina calif was nationals recruitment and fundraising nerve 
center friends of allison was a major tributary of lifesavers 
then lifesavers and national split in a pending court case in 
minneapolis lifesavers says it now is a registry in itself it 
enlisted 100000 donors for national in the past and wants to share 
them national wants sole rights to them 
dr rudolf brutoco founder and chairman of lifesavers said he 
was disgusted by delays at national that wasted patients precious 
time but it was lifesavers success that helped overload the 
system backing up lab tests and paperwork at the donor centers 
when the atlases began their search national had gathered 
57000 donors in three years 
the money the program had allocated for blood typing paid for 
1300 new donors a year the atlases brought in that many in two 
days 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

