a government witness in the conflict of 
interest case against neil bush says the presidents son lost his 
ethical moorings but did not try to deceive anyone while a 
director of a denver savings and loan 
in testimony released tuesday by the federal office of thrift 
supervision university of colorado professor edward j conry wrote 
that the 35yearold bush did not lie try to conceal or mislead 
still neil bushs conduct was unethical because he placed 
himself in situations where his selfinterest or loyalty to others 
was in competition with the interests of depositors shareholders 
insurers and taxpayers wrote conry a professor of business law 
and ethics 
he became ethically myopic unaware that his perspective or 
conduct were biased he said 
neil bush was a director of silverado banking savings and loan 
association of denver which collapsed in december 1988 at a cost 
to taxpayers of 1 billion 
