<TEXT>
two thousand western union corp employees 
got their jobs back wednesday as the company signed a tentative 
labor contract that rescinded a fourday lockout of union workers 
company and union officials said 
the twoyear settlement reached at 330 am wednesday 
guarantees the same level of health benefits and a 35 percent 
annual wage increase to the employees who are represented by the 
communications workers of america 
about half the workers covered by the contract are recording 
operators the others include technicians clerical workers and a 
smaller number scattered in other departments 
the contract also applies to 500 cwa employees not affected by 
the saturday morning lockout 
settlement of the labor dispute will free the company to 
concentrate on its proposed recapitalization plan which is 
essential to western unions future said robert j amman western 
union president 
the companys old contract with union workers expired aug 6 
workers had authorized a strike two weeks ago but the union never 
threatened to strike even after the lockout was declared said dan 
j beckstead the unions chief negotiator 
the company probably started moving when they realized the 
union and the membership was not going to crack under their 
pressure of a lockout beckstead said 
employees who were locked out will be reinstated with full back 
pay rosenthal said temporary replacements who had been staffing 
the companys principal facilities since saturday were withdrawn 
wednesday as union employees returned to work western union 
spokesman warren bechtel said 
beckstead said an unfair labor practice charge filed on monday 
with the national labor relations board would be dropped the 
complaint alleged that the company violated federal labor law by 
selectively locking out the 2000 workers 
the contract must be ratified by union members said cwa 
spokesman steven rosenthal he said ballots will be mailed by next 
week with the tally expected to be completed by early september 
the contract maintains pensions at current levels and retains a 
profitsharing program that was created in 1985 to compensate 
workers for wage and benefits concessions rosenthal said 
union negotiators made some concessions on the companys ability 
to contract work to outside firms and on the use of parttime 
employees bechtel said 
much of the debate at the threeweeklong talks centered on the 
companys attempts to curtail medical benefits bechtel said the 
company dropped its efforts to reduce medical benefits as part of 
the normal bargaining process 
the agreement came hours before western unions adjourned annual 
meeting was scheduled to reconvene the meeting to continue at 2 
pm thursday will focus on the debtridden companys proposed 
recapitalization plan 
under the plan western union wants shareholders to approve the 
reclassification of preferred shares into common shares 
a twothirds vote of the preferred shareholders is needed to 
approve the plan bechtel said 
the proposal also asks bondholders to allow the company to swap 
530 million in highyield notes for new notes paying lower 
interest rates and common shares 
noteholders originally had until midnight wednesday to turn in 
their bonds but that deadline will be extended bechtel said 
