<TEXT>
tighter controls against air pollution will push 
petroleum companies to devise new formulas for nearly all the 
gasoline sold in america by the end of the century according to a 
study released wednesday 
the study by the arthur d little management consulting firm 
predicts domestic refiners will spend up to 22 billion to alter 
their gasoline one result would be higher gasoline prices 
the changes would mark the most significant shift in gasoline 
production since companies started making unleaded fuel in the 
1970s said carlton jones who helped write the study 
a driving force behind the change will be legislation to amend 
the federal clean air act jones said both the us house and 
senate have approved bills that would require companies to 
reformulate their gasoline the goal is to reduce emissions of 
pollutants such as carbon monoxide 
the legislation would require reformulated gasoline to be sold 
in nine metropolitan areas that represent about 21 percent of the 
nations population jones said those areas which have high ozone 
concentrations are new york chicago los angeles hartford 
philadelphia baltimore milwaukee houston and san diego 
the requirement would take effect in 1993 but other forces 
could lead the movement to spread around the country jones said 
for example distributors might face logistical problems if they 
try to continue providing gasoline made under current formulas 
while at the same time providing the reformulated product 
also petroleum companies might broaden the sale of reformulated 
gasoline as a competitive wedge 
if one company advertises that its reformulated gas burns more 
cleanly consumers might want to buy that jones said 
some companies already have begun to change their formulas 
shell oil co introduced a new gasoline formula this year in the 
nine areas targeted by the federal legislation said norman 
altstedter a company spokesman 
altstedter acknowledged there was a competitive aspect to 
the companys decision but he said our first thing is to help 
improve air quality 
but the petroleum industry objects to the legislation proposed 
in congress 
our position is the government should not be writing formulas 
for gasoline said rg ensz spokesman for the american 
petroleum institute an industry trade association 
the government should set certain air quality goals and let 
the auto and petroleum industries figure out how to meet those 
goals he said 
along those lines automobile and oil companies have joined to 
conduct a comprehensive study of cleaner burning fuels ensz said 
he predicted some small refiners could be put out of business if 
the government adopts unworkable formulas 
the study itself says the investments required to meet tighter 
environmental standards may be unprofitable for refiners 
to make the new formulas companies would not simply be able to 
adjust current operations but would have to install new processing 
equipment that refiners dont usually have jones said 
the study predicts reformulated gasoline will cost consumers an 
additional 7 to 12 cents per gallon 
the study also looked at the european market but predicted the 
push for new gasoline formulas will proceed more slowly there this 
is partly because the united state has been more active in imposing 
strict emissions requirements and also because europe has less 
severe smog problems 
another variable in the equation however is the political 
crisis in the middle east jones said he did not expect the crisis 
would have much effect although an extended drop in oil supplies 
could delay implementation of federal regulations 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

