a federal judge wednesday extended an order 
freezing the assets of fundamerica inc but refused to appoint a 
receiver to protect the marketing companys assets until bankruptcy 
papers are filed thursday 
the preliminary injunction issued by us district judge marilyn 
hall patel was similar to a temporary restraining order that froze 
the assets last month 
attorneys for the plaintiffs in a 150 million classaction 
lawsuit asked patel to appoint a receiver for the company but were 
denied 
patel said that since fundamericas attorneys said they plan to 
seek protection from creditors while reorganizing under chapter 11 
of federal bankruptcy laws thursday a receiver is unnecessary 
i dont intend to appoint a receiver for a day a dubious 
position and just one more person who will have to be paid from the 
funds of fundamerica she said 
receivers are appointed by judges to manage troubled companies 
until a court rules on claims brought against the firm 
she said the preliminary injunction freezing assets would remain 
in effect until a trustee is appointed by bankruptcy court to run 
the companys affairs 
company founder and former president robert edwards is charged 
in florida with fraud for allegedly bilking club members out of 
82 million in an illegal pyramid scheme 
fundamerica sold memberships in a discount buying club that 
offered rebates on services such as mci longdistance calls and a 
range of consumer products various levels of memberships were sold 
through network marketing and multilevel sales 
attorneys in four states florida washington texas and 
california have alleged fundamerica may have run a pyramid scheme 
by selling multiple memberships to club members that they in turn 
could sell the company maintains it is a legitimate consumer 
buying club 
the class action suit seeks compensation for an undetermined 
number of members who did not recoup their total investment in the 
club patel certified the class in the suit on wednesday 
